# Review of Lesson 2.13 – Risk Management Frameworks and Standards

The final lesson introduced the internationally recognized frameworks that organizations use to establish structured and consistent risk management programs.

We examined several of the most widely adopted frameworks:

### ISO 31000

Provides internationally recognized guidance for enterprise risk management.

---

### COSO Enterprise Risk Management (ERM)

Integrates governance, strategy, performance, and enterprise risk management.

---

### ISO/IEC 27005

Provides guidance for information security risk management and supports ISO/IEC 27001 Information Security Management Systems (ISMS).

---

### NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF)

Provides a structured lifecycle for managing cybersecurity and information system risks.

---

### NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)

Provides a flexible framework organized around six core functions:

- Govern
- Identify
- Protect
- Detect
- Respond
- Recover

Rather than selecting a single framework, many organizations integrate multiple standards to support governance, cybersecurity, operational resilience, regulatory compliance, and enterprise-wide risk management.

